15/05/2003
WASHINGTON, United States -- On Wednesday (14 May), President George W Bush and Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan discussed relations between the two countries, as well as the situations in Cyprus, Iraq and the Middle East.
According to White House spokesman Ari Fleischer, the two leaders noted the freedom of movement between both parts of Cyprus and expressed hope that a lasting solution will be found to reunite the island.
Bush once again reaffirmed US support for the UN plan for Cyprus.
Also Wednesday, the office of Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi denied a report by the Turkish newspaper <I>Hurriyet</I>, which had quoted Berlusconi as saying that Turkey's EU membership is not related to resolving the Cyprus dispute.
(AFP, Anadolu Agency, CNA, NTV - 14/05/03)
